        "title": "Non-blocking ODBC calls in Java",
        "body": "<p>I use pretty standard Java ODBC functionality - grab a <code>Connection<\/code> from the pool, create a <code>Statement<\/code> and execute it.<\/p>\n\n<p>Our use-case is a game, logging game progress - ODBC calls are largely calls to stored procedures and in most cases there are no return values. So the fact the ODBC call blocks is annoying - the game is already turn based but users can see longer pauses if the DB is slow.<\/p>\n\n<p>If I don't need to check the result of an ODBC call, is there any built-in functionality to execute the statement asyncronously? If not, what is a good way to do this without writing lots of code? I DO still need to catch ODBC exceptions when and if they occur.<\/p>\n\n<p>This question looks related although not identical... <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4087696/is-asynchronous-jdbc-call-possible\">Is asynchronous jdbc call possible?<\/a><\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 14964833,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "jdbc",
            "java-6"
        ],
